{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1162dce3-84c3-472c-a229-b0723229fb4a","content":"There's no documentation about this in the current repository, but here's the general guidance from .NET/macOS knowledge:\n\n**Recovering a macOS crash dump without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — run `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching your app.\n\n2. **Check macOS crash reports** — look in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` for `.crash` or `.ips` files generated automatically by macOS.\n\n3. **Check `/cores/`** — macOS writes core dumps to `/cores/core.<pid>`. Ensure the directory exists and is writable:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n4. **Use `lldb` to analyze** — attach to the core file:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **If `/cores/` is empty** — macOS may have System Integrity Protection (SIP) restrictions. Check with `csrutil status`. On newer macOS versions, core dumps for some processes may be suppressed.\n\n6. **Alternative: use `lldb` to catch the crash live** —\n   ```bash\n   lldb /path/to/your/app\n   run\n   # after crash:\n   bt        # backtrace\n   process save-core output.core\n   ```\n\nNativeAOT apps don't bundle `createdump`, so the OS-level mechanisms (`/cores/`, DiagnosticReports, or `lldb`) are your primary options on macOS.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d817c473-2a45-44f8-b8a2-b2396f83f2a2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository appears to be empty or doesn't contain relevant documentation about this topic. Let me answer from my general knowledge about macOS crash dumps for NativeAOT apps.","outputTokens":428,"requestId":"D7C2:97405:1022B8D:127E74F:69F2B60D"},"id":"0bcfb3a5-776d-4316-b7ce-3b380e930b9f","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:53:28.091Z","parentId":"0348f82b-c32b-4466-b9b4-4549a16424d7"}
